Introduction

The estimation of statistical models of Tines research are replicated in this document, making use of Bayesian anlaysis. For the analyses I used the brms package.

Preparation

Before we can start we have to load the necessary dataset and the packages needed for the analyses.

library(gganimate)
library(brms)
library(bayesplot)
library(sjstats)
library(tidybayes)
library(purrr)
library(ggplot2)
load("03A MathAnalysis.RData")

This loads three datasets:

  • Math1
  • Math12
  • MathSorted

The datasets contain outliers that are allready defined. A dummy-variable indicates whether an observation is an outlier or not \(outlier_PerD\). In the next block of code we create two new dataframes that no longer contain the outliers.

Analyses

Model 0

We start by analysing a null-model for comparison reasons only. The following command estimates the model. Four chains of 5000 iterations are used. The estimation runs on two separate cores.

To get an idea of the built-in priors used by brms we make use of the prior_summary() command:

prior_summary(Math1_H12_0)

A first check is on how the estimation of all the parameters went, we can use the plot() command. The plots at the righthand side show the typical hairy catterpillars we want to see. None of the four chains show strange patterns.

To get a summary of the information in the posterior distribution, whe can make use of the summary() command.

To interpret the effect of the number of comparisons made on judgement time, we have to intepret both the linear and the quadratic term in the model. The estimation of the linear growth parameter is negative with the 95% most probable parameter estimates varrying between -4.68 and -2.13. The 95% most probable parameter estimates for the quadratic term varry between 0.88 to 5.59 and are all positive. Further on we will create an annimated graph to assist the interpretation of this growth curve.

Our model also contains estimates of the variances at assessor level. The two substantially most interesting parameters are the sd for the effect of number of comparison and the correlation between intercept and slope. The standard deviation demonstrating the differences between assessors in the impact of the nth number of comparison is 95% most probably a value between 0.37 and 2.79, which implies that we can confidently conclude that the fact that judgement time doesnt evolve similarly during the process of conducting multiple comparisons. The 95% most probable estimates of the correlation between intercepts and slopes at assessor level varry between -0.96 and 0.21. Allthough the majority of the estimates in the posterior are negative we can not exclude the probability that this correlation is close to zero or even positive.

 Family: gaussian 
  Links: mu = log; sigma = identity

is a crude measure of effective sample size, and Rhat is the potential
